social democratic parties have responded, at the national as well as at the European Union level. A wide range of leading political scientists provide the reader with an in-depth understanding of the prospects for social democracy in the midst of an unprecedented crisis for neoliberalism. The book draws together some of the most well-known and prestigious scholars of social democracy and social democratic parties, along with a number of impressive new scholars in the field, to present a compelling and up to date analysis of social democratic fortunes in the contemporary period. It benefits from an analysis of social democratic parties’ experiences in 6 different countries – the UK, Sweden, Germany, France, Spain and Greece – along with a number of chapters on the fate of social democracy in the institutions of the EU.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 06. Mrz 2024) 0aGlobal Financial Crisis, 2008-2009xPolitical aspectszEuropean Union countries. 0aSocialist partieszEurope. 4aPolitical Studies 2020. 7aPOLITICAL SCIENCE / Political Ideologies / Communism, Post-Communism & Socialism.2bisacsh  aBritish Labour Party.  aEuropean Union.  aEuropean social democracy.  aGordon Brown.  aGreat Recession.  aParty of European Socialists.  aTony Blair.  aglobal economic crisis.  aneo-liberal consensus.  apolitical economy.  asouthern Europe.  asupranational re-social democratization.  athere is no alternative.  awestern Europe.1 aAndersson, Jenny, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBailey, David J., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBailey, David J., eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aBouillaud, Christophe, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aCallaghan, John, econtributor.4ctb4https://id